Here's how to implement all three pieces:

**1. Custom "Cancel" back button on `EditProductPage.xaml`:**

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                           Command="{Binding BackCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- your form content -->
</ContentPage>
```

**2. ViewModel with the back command and unsaved-changes flag:**

```csharp
public partial class EditProductViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    bool hasUnsavedChanges;

    [RelayCommand]
    async Task Back()
    {
        if (HasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "Discard your changes?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (!discard) return;
        }

        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    }
}
```

**3. Guard the hardware/gesture back in `AppShell.xaml.cs`:**

The custom `BackButtonBehavior.Command` handles the Shell back button, but the system back gesture (Android swipe, hardware button) fires through `OnNavigating`. Guard it there:

```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    if (args.Source != ShellNavigationSource.Pop)
        return;

    if (Shell.Current.CurrentPage?.BindingContext
            is EditProductViewModel { HasUnsavedChanges: true } vm)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "Discard your changes?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- `BackButtonBehavior` replaces the arrow with "Cancel" and routes taps to your command.
- `OnNavigating` + `GetDeferral()` intercepts the system back gesture asynchronously — you **must** call `deferral.Complete()` or navigation hangs.
- Both paths check `HasUnsavedChanges` so the dialog only appears when there's something to lose.
